snippet.textDisplay:
EDIT: @Scoober (see below) prompted me to look at their website. Actually, this isn't too bad of a concept. Though, it does face some uphill battles. The main one being that, with something like eye-bolts, you'd test/rate them with a pull-test. If this rests against a wall without its own rated dead-weight system in place, you can't ever say that its safe when deployed unless its properly 'installed' (meaning is actually affixed to a rated wall - because the device can't guarantee the structural integrity of any surface it might be put against. That is a factor against it, and a relevant one if it's after a lot of accreditation in the industry, but fall restraint which is what I see it is being used for is a bit more relaxed than fall arrest or fall suspension (abseiling). At any rate, I rushed in with my comments a little bit and I apologise if I misled anyone. My original comment resumes below!

This one is interesting to me because I'm a former rope access technician / abseiler and I've worked in this industry pretty extensively. I don't feel qualified to comment on the Sashmate, but I am about the Stronghold. So, basically, it's a junk product. He won't be able to sell it for several reasons. There are tons of man-anchors on the market already and they're all superior because they do the same job more effectively and cheaper. With this one, you have to lug it to location, assemble it, and drill a ton of fixings in. A couple of tested/rated eye-bolts would be a ton cheaper, easier to install, and are perfectly safe to use. Alternatively, a rail system would also be less disruptive and would be more flexible. Most industrial abseiling jobs (what this is really for) are to fix temporary issues (aside from window cleaning, but you'd always go with something like a rail or eyebolt system in those instances - no contest) and so you wouldn't want it installed permanently most of the time. Knowing that, a flat/deadweight man anchor or an a-frame both do the same job and are much cheaper and don't require any drilling/fixing. Basically, this is too bulky/inefficient/expensive to compete with other temporary access systems, and too awkward/bulky/expensive to compete with permanent systems. It's not terrible in and of itself, it's just that there's two purposes/markets for this (temporary and permanent) and I'd go to half a dozen alternatives that are better in either instances. So would anyone else in the industry buying something like this. He's right that it's much better than scaffolding, but it's not a good solution compared to already existing solutions. I'm sure he probably does have a patent on it too, because he can probably patent its form factor, it doesn't matter though because other ones are still better alternatives and aren't affected by his patent.
